00:02:11.549 --> 00:02:20.040
I'll just, I guess, talk a little bit about
this film.

00:02:20.040 --> 00:02:27.159
It started when we were doing this thing called
Kentucky Fried Theater.

00:02:27.159 --> 00:02:33.549
And Kentucky Fried Theater was live skits
and also we had a video monitor.

00:02:33.549 --> 00:02:39.969
This was really in the early days of video
with reel-to-reel video in this big machine.

00:02:39.969 --> 00:02:42.189
It's like this big.

00:02:42.189 --> 00:02:47.940
And it is amazing 'cause the machine was like
this big, and half inch reel-to-reel and really

00:02:47.940 --> 00:02:48.940
heavy.

00:02:48.940 --> 00:02:51.150
And a big cord tethered to a camera.

00:02:51.150 --> 00:02:55.409
And it was black and white and not nearly
as good as my iPhone.

00:02:55.409 --> 00:02:56.409
You know.

00:02:56.409 --> 00:02:57.609
In terms of picture quality.

00:02:57.609 --> 00:03:01.989
[laughter] So it's hard to imagine how they,
how you do that.

00:03:01.989 --> 00:03:08.950
But the, so we used to set the video tape
machine to go on in the middle of the night

00:03:08.950 --> 00:03:12.060
where some of the corniest commercials were.

00:03:12.060 --> 00:03:14.909
'Cause we would do spoofs on them.

00:03:14.909 --> 00:03:20.040
And one night we caught this movie called
"Zero Hour" which is this 1957 flying movie

00:03:20.040 --> 00:03:26.840
with Dana Andrews, Sterling Hayden, Elroy
Hirsch, being some fairly well known names

00:03:26.840 --> 00:03:27.840
at the time.

00:03:27.840 --> 00:03:31.299
They probably don't mean a lot to you now
but--.

00:03:31.299 --> 00:03:36.489
And we were looking at the commercials but
then we kinda got engrossed in the movie.

00:03:36.489 --> 00:03:45.659
And the interesting thing about this movie
and the whole genre, it kind of was that we

00:03:45.659 --> 00:03:47.299
made fun of it.

00:03:47.299 --> 00:03:48.780
But we also loved it.

00:03:48.780 --> 00:03:49.780
You know?

00:03:49.780 --> 00:03:54.090
And that sort of, everything we did in terms
of satire, we had to have both.

00:03:54.090 --> 00:03:58.629
We had to find it laughable and we also had
to have some affection for it.

00:03:58.629 --> 00:04:04.040
And I think you can kind of see that in "Airplane."

00:04:04.040 --> 00:04:10.530
And a lot, you know, for us it was this really
tough, hard-hitting style of drama that we

00:04:10.530 --> 00:04:11.920
grew up with.

00:04:11.920 --> 00:04:14.169
Both on TV and in the movies.

00:04:14.169 --> 00:04:18.570
The B movies in particular.

00:04:18.570 --> 00:04:22.230
And the Charlton Heston school, whatever.

00:04:22.230 --> 00:04:23.230
Anyway.

00:04:23.230 --> 00:04:28.390
And so we said "Gee, maybe we should make,
this would make a funny movie."

00:04:28.390 --> 00:04:32.320
And so we didn't really know a lot about writing
movies.

00:04:32.320 --> 00:04:40.410
But we took, the three of us, while we were
doing the show, or, were working on it.

00:04:40.410 --> 00:04:44.450
And then we put it down for a while 'cause
we couldn't.

00:04:44.450 --> 00:04:47.220
We finished it but we couldn't get it going.

00:04:47.220 --> 00:04:50.010
Interestingly enough, someone offered to buy
it.

00:04:50.010 --> 00:04:53.880
But we didn't wanna sell it 'cause we didn't
trust anybody to do it right.

00:04:53.880 --> 00:04:57.750
And even when we were nothing, we had, we
didn't have anything.

00:04:57.750 --> 00:05:00.952
And I think someone was offering us a couple
hundred thousand dollars or something if it

00:05:00.952 --> 00:05:03.040
got made, and that may have been a lot of
money.

00:05:03.040 --> 00:05:08.670
But we grew to love it and we didn't want
anybody to mess it up.

00:05:08.670 --> 00:05:12.500
Particularly the casting which was probably
the most important thing to us.

00:05:12.500 --> 00:05:13.820
Well, two things.

00:05:13.820 --> 00:05:17.010
They're part of the same thing.

00:05:17.010 --> 00:05:19.280
The casting and the tone.

00:05:19.280 --> 00:05:22.460
To play it totally straight.

00:05:22.460 --> 00:05:28.120
When we were on the set we used to, and when
we spoke with the actors before we hired them,

00:05:28.120 --> 00:05:31.790
we told them "We don't want you to play it
straight.

00:05:31.790 --> 00:05:34.980
We want you to pretend that you don't know
you're in a comedy."

00:05:34.980 --> 00:05:35.980
And there's a difference.

00:05:35.980 --> 00:05:39.060
'Cause when you say "play it straight", a
lot of people kinda think they're playing

00:05:39.060 --> 00:05:40.170
it straight.

00:05:40.170 --> 00:05:46.450
But really they're, it's for the actor it's
about still about them being funny.

00:05:46.450 --> 00:05:48.420
And them making people laugh.

00:05:48.420 --> 00:05:51.640
And we really, that's what we really wanted
to reign in.

00:05:51.640 --> 00:05:55.500
You act like you have no idea that this is
funny.

00:05:55.500 --> 00:05:56.500
[laughter]

00:05:56.500 --> 00:05:59.280
That you think you're doing a serious movie.

00:05:59.280 --> 00:06:02.570
And that's kinda why we just didn't trust
anybody.

00:06:02.570 --> 00:06:06.450
And insisted on directing it when we finally
did get to Paramount.

00:06:06.450 --> 00:06:08.410
And they said "OK."

00:06:08.410 --> 00:06:10.440
They said they liked the script.

00:06:10.440 --> 00:06:16.790
They tried to, they brought up names of current
movie directors that were established successful

00:06:16.790 --> 00:06:20.490
directors and wanted someone else to direct
it.

00:06:20.490 --> 00:06:25.800
And we kind of said, no, we need to do that.

00:06:25.800 --> 00:06:30.810
It was really for that reason, not that we
thought we were gonna be great directors.

00:06:30.810 --> 00:06:37.430
But we just, this was our baby and even the--.

00:06:37.430 --> 00:06:40.200
Every studio in town turned it down until
we got to Paramount.

00:06:40.200 --> 00:06:47.760
And Michael Eisner was having dinner with
a woman named Susan Baerwald, who was a reader

00:06:47.760 --> 00:06:49.450
at United Artists.

00:06:49.450 --> 00:06:55.740
And he said "What have you read recently that
you like?"

00:06:55.740 --> 00:06:59.190
And she said "Well, there's this one script,
'Airplane'."

00:06:59.190 --> 00:07:06.710
And she described the film to him and said
"I sent it through with high recommendations

00:07:06.710 --> 00:07:08.630
and they passed on it."

00:07:08.630 --> 00:07:14.290
And Eisner got up from the table, called Jeff
Katzenberg and said "Track this thing down."

00:07:14.290 --> 00:07:19.790
'Cause he just thought that sounded, a comedy
on an airplane, was a great idea.

00:07:19.790 --> 00:07:24.080
And the idea that it was low budget.

00:07:24.080 --> 00:07:26.530
[laughter]

00:07:26.530 --> 00:07:30.670
And so they were great.

00:07:30.670 --> 00:07:31.990
And they were helpful.

00:07:31.990 --> 00:07:34.020
And there's another interesting thing.

00:07:34.020 --> 00:07:37.970
Eisner insisted, we had written it to be done
on a prop plane.

00:07:37.970 --> 00:07:40.140
Because that's what "Zero Hour" was.

00:07:40.140 --> 00:07:42.790
And in fact I think we wanted to do it black
and white, even.

00:07:42.790 --> 00:07:45.810
Because we were so, we were too into that
whole thing.

00:07:45.810 --> 00:07:51.760
And Eisner, to his credit, said "No."

00:07:51.760 --> 00:07:59.610
Well what he said was, he said "You can do
it in black and white and with a prop plane

00:07:59.610 --> 00:08:02.400
but not at this studio."

00:08:02.400 --> 00:08:04.200
[laughter]

00:08:04.200 --> 00:08:12.290
But I always, I've talked to him recently
and I always thank him.

00:08:12.290 --> 00:08:16.430
He was absolutely right about that.

00:08:16.430 --> 00:08:20.550
And, but what they never really quite, the
casting.

00:08:20.550 --> 00:08:25.840
They said "OK, OK, you can have Nielsen and
Bridges and Stack."

00:08:25.840 --> 00:08:27.890
'Cause we were very insistent about that.

00:08:27.890 --> 00:08:30.890
But they wanted to put a lot of comedy cameos
in it.

00:08:30.890 --> 00:08:39.079
People from, actors that were on TV shows
at the time, on the lot Robin Williams, and

00:08:39.079 --> 00:08:48.009
Penny Marshall, and all the Paramount TV show
people, and others.

00:08:48.009 --> 00:08:51.000
And, which we didn't really wanna do.

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:55.209
But we went through this process and fortunately
we had this great, one of the producers Howard

00:08:55.209 --> 00:08:56.209
W. Koch.

00:08:56.209 --> 00:08:57.959
He's not with us anymore.

00:08:57.959 --> 00:08:59.540
Wonderful, great guy.

00:08:59.540 --> 00:09:04.759
Who at first we thought "Gee, the studio put
him on" and we thought "Ah, do we really want

00:09:04.759 --> 00:09:06.959
this old guy on this movie."

00:09:06.959 --> 00:09:11.350
And, of course, at the time he was the age
I am now.

00:09:11.350 --> 00:09:12.949
[laughter]

00:09:12.949 --> 00:09:14.529
But he was terrific.

00:09:14.529 --> 00:09:16.699
And he would call--.

00:09:16.699 --> 00:09:20.230
He got what we wanted to do.

00:09:20.230 --> 00:09:25.120
And so he would call agents and say "You know
what, I'm offering your client this script.

00:09:25.120 --> 00:09:28.910
But it's not really gonna be any good."

00:09:28.910 --> 00:09:30.410
[laughter]

00:09:30.410 --> 00:09:31.410
And they would pass.

00:09:31.410 --> 00:09:34.540
And the only one that we ended up with out
of those is Jimmy Walker.

00:09:34.540 --> 00:09:36.139
Who is, you know, with the big thing.

00:09:36.139 --> 00:09:37.629
Which was fine.

00:09:37.629 --> 00:09:43.280
But it wasn't until the first day of dailies
that we got a call from the studio and they

00:09:43.280 --> 00:09:50.399
said, and that was the first day of shooting
was Leslie Neilsen in the cockpit saying "I

00:09:50.399 --> 00:09:51.399
am serious.

00:09:51.399 --> 00:09:52.399
And don't call me Shirley."

00:09:52.399 --> 00:09:55.220
Among other things.

00:09:55.220 --> 00:09:57.269
And they said "Oh, now we get it."

00:09:57.269 --> 00:09:58.269
[laughter]

00:09:58.269 --> 00:10:03.200
They really, and I have to say, I don't call
anybody.

00:10:03.200 --> 00:10:09.870
Most people really didn't get that and I don't
think, I don't you know ridicule people for

00:10:09.870 --> 00:10:14.630
that because it was a difficult concept to
catch, to understand.

00:10:14.630 --> 00:10:17.389
Until you really saw how it played.

00:10:17.389 --> 00:10:22.550
And for us, this was something we had done
in our videos.

00:10:22.550 --> 00:10:25.559
Even with younger actors, just playing it.

00:10:25.559 --> 00:10:27.110
Not famous of course.

00:10:27.110 --> 00:10:29.120
Just playing it straight.

00:10:29.120 --> 00:10:33.709
So it, we were, we had a great experience.

00:10:33.709 --> 00:10:38.360
It was helpful for us that we were this little
three million dollar movie.

00:10:38.360 --> 00:10:44.209
And at the same time, they were dealing with
the first Star Trek movie.

00:10:44.209 --> 00:10:45.670
Which was going way over budget.

00:10:45.670 --> 00:10:48.649
So they didn't pay any attention to us.

00:10:48.649 --> 00:10:49.649
[laughter]

00:10:49.649 --> 00:10:52.490
Which is great and we got the movie made.

00:10:52.490 --> 00:10:54.379
The first screening was a disaster.

00:10:54.379 --> 00:10:58.460
I mean, they brought in, we, it was longer.

00:10:58.460 --> 00:11:01.329
This movie now is 97 minutes.

00:11:01.329 --> 00:11:08.009
And I think, and the first one was probably
an hour and 50 minutes.

00:11:08.009 --> 00:11:14.069
We just sort of, you know, your first screenings
generally are long and then you.

00:11:14.069 --> 00:11:20.420
With satires we go into every movie hoping
that we have 90 minutes that are funny.

00:11:20.420 --> 00:11:25.040
But you're always surprised.

00:11:25.040 --> 00:11:28.449
And that first screening is always the scariest.

00:11:28.449 --> 00:11:29.490
You know?

00:11:29.490 --> 00:11:34.589
But in this case, and we hadn't had, it was
the first film we directed, so we hadn't had

00:11:34.589 --> 00:11:35.920
a lot of experience with that.

00:11:35.920 --> 00:11:43.529
But the guy whose job it was to recruit, they
insisted on doing it on the lot.

00:11:43.529 --> 00:11:47.939
The guy didn't do a great job of recruiting.

00:11:47.939 --> 00:11:54.600
It, to his defense, it's not that easy to
recruit an audience of people for a comedy

00:11:54.600 --> 00:11:55.920
starring Robert Stack.

00:11:55.920 --> 00:11:58.760
[laughter] And Leslie Neilsen and Jeffrey
Green.

00:11:58.760 --> 00:12:00.240
Lloyd Bridges and Peter Graves.

00:12:00.240 --> 00:12:08.660
So they ended up dragging people off the line
from "Mork and Mindy" and "Happy Days" and

00:12:08.660 --> 00:12:10.170
all of whatever they were shooting.

00:12:10.170 --> 00:12:14.420
And they just, they were, they just weren't
laughing.

00:12:14.420 --> 00:12:15.899
Except for one guy.

00:12:15.899 --> 00:12:23.410
It was one guy in the audience that "Ah-ha-ha-ha-ha"
He just loved it.

00:12:23.410 --> 00:12:24.790
He just kept laughing.

00:12:24.790 --> 00:12:28.910
And bless him on beyond, you know a lot of
times people don't like to laugh if everybody

00:12:28.910 --> 00:12:29.910
else isn't.

00:12:29.910 --> 00:12:30.910
But this guy didn't care.

00:12:30.910 --> 00:12:34.759
He's just "Wah-ha-haaaa".

00:12:34.759 --> 00:12:37.139
And we edited off of one guy.

00:12:37.139 --> 00:12:38.199
[laughter]

00:12:38.199 --> 00:12:45.749
You know, you really, you usually try to figure
you want a representative.

00:12:45.749 --> 00:12:47.430
You want 300 people.

00:12:47.430 --> 00:12:49.009
500 to get a sense.

00:12:49.009 --> 00:12:50.910
'Cause everybody doesn't laugh and.

00:12:50.910 --> 00:12:52.369
One guy.

00:12:52.369 --> 00:12:53.720
[laughter]

00:12:53.720 --> 00:13:00.459
So then, the, afterwards, people were coming,
studio people.

00:13:00.459 --> 00:13:02.009
And "Well, now, I guess you got a lot of work
here."

00:13:02.009 --> 00:13:07.610
And we could see the "Failure!" in their eyes.

00:13:07.610 --> 00:13:11.820
[laughter] Actually I should say there was
a screening before that.

00:13:11.820 --> 00:13:17.949
That was a funny, the first time we showed
it to the studio, we showed it to Eisner and

00:13:17.949 --> 00:13:20.290
I think Katzenberg, too.

00:13:20.290 --> 00:13:23.100
And we showed it at Eisner's house, in his
screening room.

00:13:23.100 --> 00:13:24.910
Of course you're not looking for big laughs.

00:13:24.910 --> 00:13:30.160
'Cause it's just a couple of guys who've read
the script, seen the dailies, etcetera, etcetera.

00:13:30.160 --> 00:13:37.449
But his kids who were younger at the time,
were, I don't know, 8 and 10 or 12, whatever.

00:13:37.449 --> 00:13:41.300
They were in the projection booth and you
could hear them laughing through the projection

00:13:41.300 --> 00:13:42.300
booth.

00:13:42.300 --> 00:13:46.850
And Eisner, to his credit, he always had faith.

00:13:46.850 --> 00:13:47.850
You know?

00:13:47.850 --> 00:13:58.170
And even when all these people said what some
of the other studio executives came out and

00:13:58.170 --> 00:13:59.170
said.

00:13:59.170 --> 00:14:00.170
More.

00:14:00.170 --> 00:14:01.170
You know.

00:14:01.170 --> 00:14:02.170
Negative things.

00:14:02.170 --> 00:14:06.019
And some who never liked the script and whatever,
were kind of saying, "I was right."

00:14:06.019 --> 00:14:10.220
Eisner and Katzenberg always had faith in
it.

00:14:10.220 --> 00:14:20.019
And so we've always, you know, had a debt
of gratitude towards them.

00:14:20.019 --> 00:14:22.720
No matter how much they tried to fuck us in
the future.

00:14:22.720 --> 00:14:23.720
[laughter]

00:14:23.720 --> 00:14:26.890
No, no I'm kidding.

00:14:26.890 --> 00:14:29.390
It's, you know.

00:14:29.390 --> 00:14:30.390
[laughter]

00:14:30.390 --> 00:14:34.319
Well, they're our studio executives, you know
what I mean?

00:14:34.319 --> 00:14:35.319
[laughter]

00:14:35.319 --> 00:14:39.350
Lemme just tell you right now, Paramount didn't
have a masseuse on duty.

00:14:39.350 --> 00:14:47.050
It's not like Google where "We want the employees
to be happy."

00:14:47.050 --> 00:14:48.279
[laughter]

00:14:48.279 --> 00:14:51.310
"A happy worker is a productive worker."

00:14:51.310 --> 00:15:00.430
That wasn't the, you could be, what Paramount,
the studios are more the 'you could be fired

00:15:00.430 --> 00:15:03.139
tomorrow' method of encouragement.

00:15:03.139 --> 00:15:04.179
[laughter]

00:15:04.179 --> 00:15:13.029
Anyway, so we finally decided we would, we
need to edit this.

00:15:13.029 --> 00:15:17.589
our next screening would be on a college campus.

00:15:17.589 --> 00:15:21.809
And we went, where was the first screening?

00:15:21.809 --> 00:15:28.629
I think it was, oh gee, somewhere, a UC campus.

00:15:28.629 --> 00:15:30.380
And forgive me, I can't think.

00:15:30.380 --> 00:15:32.649
Davis, maybe it was.

00:15:32.649 --> 00:15:36.230
And that was like, exhilarating.

00:15:36.230 --> 00:15:38.019
Because they just loved it.

00:15:38.019 --> 00:15:39.230
We, it was better edited, too.

00:15:39.230 --> 00:15:41.980
Because thanks to that one guy.

00:15:41.980 --> 00:15:44.199
[laughter] I should have gotten his name.

00:15:44.199 --> 00:15:45.670
I should really.

00:15:45.670 --> 00:15:48.009
Still I'd like to call him and thank him.

00:15:48.009 --> 00:15:52.569
But then we did a bunch of college campus
screenings.

00:15:52.569 --> 00:15:56.160
And those were just great.

00:15:56.160 --> 00:16:02.350
And then, there's just nothing worse than
spending years of your life on a movie and

00:16:02.350 --> 00:16:03.759
feeling like it's bombing.

00:16:03.759 --> 00:16:12.209
And it's really, it's, we all have a lot of,
I don't know if it's the same in your business

00:16:12.209 --> 00:16:13.209
exactly.

00:16:13.209 --> 00:16:20.220
But for filmmakers, we have so much of our
own personal whatever tied up in it.

00:16:20.220 --> 00:16:25.550
And own egos and worth and all of that kind
of stuff.

00:16:25.550 --> 00:16:27.220
That it really, it's hard.

00:16:27.220 --> 00:16:30.230
You have to learn not to "zzzz-zzzz-zzzz"
you know.

00:16:30.230 --> 00:16:36.239
Because that's the way the business is for
most people.

00:16:36.239 --> 00:16:40.749
But it, you know, those screenings were great.

00:16:40.749 --> 00:16:46.220
And then pretty much from there it was fairly
smooth.

00:16:46.220 --> 00:16:50.220
And then it came one, it was a hit.

00:16:50.220 --> 00:17:00.449
But oddly enough, it's funny, I don't think
when we made it then, we ever thought it would

00:17:00.449 --> 00:17:02.850
still be around 30 years later.

00:17:02.850 --> 00:17:03.850
[laughter]

00:17:03.850 --> 00:17:05.319
And people would still, you know what I mean.

00:17:05.319 --> 00:17:08.480
And of course we didn't know about, that was
before video.

00:17:08.480 --> 00:17:13.189
In those days, a movie had a second release.

00:17:13.189 --> 00:17:15.920
Or a re-release.

00:17:15.920 --> 00:17:20.370
And so they would like six months later, if
a movie was successful enough, they'd put

00:17:20.370 --> 00:17:22.760
it out in theaters again for people who'd
missed it.

00:17:22.760 --> 00:17:30.970
And then it was just the television, a few
networks that would periodically maybe show

00:17:30.970 --> 00:17:32.179
a movie.

00:17:32.179 --> 00:17:37.809
But there was some movies kind of died off
unless they were like "Wizard of Oz" or some,

00:17:37.809 --> 00:17:41.029
"Gone with the Wind" the big movies.

00:17:41.029 --> 00:17:48.830
But thanks to video, and DVD now, these things
live.

00:17:48.830 --> 00:17:52.169
And so it's amazing.

00:17:52.169 --> 00:18:00.890
That this thing that we did when we were kids
with, you know.

00:18:00.890 --> 00:18:06.919
Sort of carried this, it's almost become more
now than it was then.

00:18:06.919 --> 00:18:07.919
In a way.

00:18:07.919 --> 00:18:08.919
It's hard for me to gauge.

00:18:08.919 --> 00:18:09.919
'Cause I'm inside it.

00:18:09.919 --> 00:18:13.210
But it feels like, I mean, people liked it
then.

00:18:13.210 --> 00:18:14.779
And it was like "Oh, that was cool."

00:18:14.779 --> 00:18:21.170
But I just, I didn't feel then quite like
the god I do know.

00:18:21.170 --> 00:18:26.120
[laughter]
&gt;&gt;male #1: We're not worthy, we're not worthy

00:18:26.120 --> 00:18:29.970
[laughs]
&gt;&gt;Jerry: [laughing] Thank you, thank you.

00:18:29.970 --> 00:18:33.620
No, it has taken on a, I think a different
aura.

00:18:33.620 --> 00:18:36.990
But anyway, so that's like a quick overview.

00:18:36.990 --> 00:18:40.010
But I'll, so I'd love to answer questions.

00:18:40.010 --> 00:18:41.010
Any questions you have.

