what?

00:18:54.670 --> 00:19:00.870
Half a dozen of this absolutely among the
funniest television ever.

00:19:00.870 --> 00:19:01.870
&gt;&gt;Jerry: Thank you.

00:19:01.870 --> 00:19:07.440
You know it was a funny thing about "Police
Squad."

00:19:07.440 --> 00:19:16.840
We had this, we insisted right off the bat
that there not be a laugh track.

00:19:16.840 --> 00:19:20.240
And so ABC said "OK", you know.

00:19:20.240 --> 00:19:22.350
They wanted to do the show.

00:19:22.350 --> 00:19:28.850
And we got into it and when it was done they
begged us to put a laugh track on it.

00:19:28.850 --> 00:19:34.110
We had contractually, we had "You can't do
this without our permission."

00:19:34.110 --> 00:19:38.500
And so because the thing is, about that kinda
humor, the whole thing is you're pretending

00:19:38.500 --> 00:19:40.730
it's not funny.

00:19:40.730 --> 00:19:47.799
And so when we finished the first show, they
wanted us to, they put a laugh track on.

00:19:47.799 --> 00:19:52.370
Not that they thought they'd sneak something
by, but they asked us, "Please just look at

00:19:52.370 --> 00:19:53.370
it.

00:19:53.370 --> 00:19:54.980
Because we think it plays much better."

00:19:54.980 --> 00:20:00.429
And we said "No, this is not our humor."

00:20:00.429 --> 00:20:02.790
But you know, for television they may have
been right.

00:20:02.790 --> 00:20:05.760
For our show, we were right.

00:20:05.760 --> 00:20:08.130
And so we never regretted the decision.

00:20:08.130 --> 00:20:13.500
But I think the real telling thing was that
Tony Thermopolis when he canceled it, said

00:20:13.500 --> 00:20:15.890
it didn't work because you had to watch it.

00:20:15.890 --> 00:20:16.890
[laughter]

00:20:16.890 --> 00:20:19.360
&gt;&gt;audience member: You had to focus.

00:20:19.360 --> 00:20:20.360
&gt;&gt;Jerry: You had to focus.

00:20:20.360 --> 00:20:22.510
And it's true, we made it like a film.

00:20:22.510 --> 00:20:27.600
Like, people sit in a darkened room facing
the screen and paying attention.

00:20:27.600 --> 00:20:35.019
And with television, kind of, you're doing
other, but now you're texting on your phone,

00:20:35.019 --> 00:20:36.230
you're doing all kinds of things.

00:20:36.230 --> 00:20:40.720
In those days it was, still you're getting
up to get something to eat or you've got a

00:20:40.720 --> 00:20:42.850
newspaper or you're talking to some people.

00:20:42.850 --> 00:20:43.850
Whatever.

00:20:43.850 --> 00:20:50.679
You're just not, and I actually heard you
know, at the time people would tell me when

00:20:50.679 --> 00:20:55.190
college students would say, they would all
get together in the dorm at the, in the lounge

00:20:55.190 --> 00:20:56.480
or whatever.

00:20:56.480 --> 00:21:00.690
And 50 or more would watch it together and
it would play great.

00:21:00.690 --> 00:21:03.090
Because then it played like a movie in a way.

00:21:03.090 --> 00:21:09.500
And it also is the kinda thing that it always
helps to have an audience for something like

00:21:09.500 --> 00:21:10.500
that.

00:21:10.500 --> 00:21:14.990
So watching at home without a laugh track,
I don't know.

00:21:14.990 --> 00:21:24.760
But for us, we had mixed feelings about it
being canceled because on the one hand, you

00:21:24.760 --> 00:21:27.150
don't like to fail at anything.

00:21:27.150 --> 00:21:32.070
But on the other hand, we didn't, it was tough
to keep the quality up.

00:21:32.070 --> 00:21:34.830
And I don't think we really quite did through
the whole thing.

00:21:34.830 --> 00:21:39.529
I mean, I thought was, from our perspective
it was a bit sporadic.

00:21:39.529 --> 00:21:42.130
Some great great stuff in it, but a little
bit sporadic.

00:21:42.130 --> 00:21:51.230
But when you consider you'd spend, we'd spend
a year to write a movie, and a year between

00:21:51.230 --> 00:21:53.990
preproduction and shooting and editing.

00:21:53.990 --> 00:21:57.010
So it's at least a two year process.

00:21:57.010 --> 00:21:58.010
Making the thing.

00:21:58.010 --> 00:22:01.909
And here we're doing 24 minutes a week.

00:22:01.909 --> 00:22:05.860
And you have a little more than that 'cause
you start a little earlier and stuff.

00:22:05.860 --> 00:22:13.639
But it's still really, and you're shooting
and doing preproduction shooting, editing,

00:22:13.639 --> 00:22:15.100
all at once.

00:22:15.100 --> 00:22:16.570
It's a three ring circus.

00:22:16.570 --> 00:22:19.799
Plus the fact that we couldnít direct them
all ourselves.

00:22:19.799 --> 00:22:25.130
We hired other people to direct it and that
was always kind of a mess because it's once

00:22:25.130 --> 00:22:29.630
again, our sense of humor.

00:22:29.630 --> 00:22:32.360
That kind of satire is just very specific.

00:22:32.360 --> 00:22:36.679
So it was hard to just find someone else who
could go in and do that.

00:22:36.679 --> 00:22:41.500
And we were not good producers for directors,
in that case.

00:22:41.500 --> 00:22:43.200
'Cause we would be saying "No, no, no."

00:22:43.200 --> 00:22:46.570
We would be stepping in all the time.

00:22:46.570 --> 00:22:49.460
And sort of directing.

00:22:49.460 --> 00:22:50.730
And anyway.

