00:28:00.360 --> 00:28:06.710
&gt;&gt;Jerry: OK, well, "Kentucky Fried Theater",
we were all at the university in Madison,

00:28:06.710 --> 00:28:07.860
University of Wisconsin.

00:28:07.860 --> 00:28:11.419
My brother, and Jim Abrams and I.

00:28:11.419 --> 00:28:14.309
And we started this theater.

00:28:14.309 --> 00:28:20.090
Actually we had seen this thing called "Groove
Tube" which was this guy named Ken Shapiro

00:28:20.090 --> 00:28:22.970
got a hold of, had some video tape equipment.

00:28:22.970 --> 00:28:27.000
And he made some, a bunch of funny videos.

00:28:27.000 --> 00:28:30.669
And what he would do is rent a theater.

00:28:30.669 --> 00:28:37.289
And do some advertising, and you'd come in
and there'd be you know, these bunch of chairs

00:28:37.289 --> 00:28:39.470
in front of a television monitor.

00:28:39.470 --> 00:28:41.809
Or a few monitors around.

00:28:41.809 --> 00:28:47.379
And he'd actually put a couple refrigerators
in there where you could go up and get a soda

00:28:47.379 --> 00:28:48.379
or something.

00:28:48.379 --> 00:28:54.190
And the idea though was that it was stuff
that you couldn't, it was TV but that you

00:28:54.190 --> 00:28:55.399
couldn't see on TV.

00:28:55.399 --> 00:28:58.580
'Cause this was before cable.

00:28:58.580 --> 00:29:01.960
And so television was pretty chaste.

00:29:01.960 --> 00:29:07.620
But this, these were all spoofs and some of
them were pretty scatological.

00:29:07.620 --> 00:29:11.149
And R-rated and whatever.

00:29:11.149 --> 00:29:16.980
And you know, we thought, "Well just, we can
do this."

00:29:16.980 --> 00:29:27.450
Actually, my, the story prior to this, a family
friend, a friend of my parents, worked, there

00:29:27.450 --> 00:29:31.129
was a, had a sickroom service company.

00:29:31.129 --> 00:29:35.450
Where they rented out wheelchairs and that
kinda thing.

00:29:35.450 --> 00:29:44.120
And he had this video tape machine that he
would use to demonstrate some of the stuff.

00:29:44.120 --> 00:29:45.820
And my father thought.

00:29:45.820 --> 00:29:52.450
He said "I talked to Bill and he said he would
let you use this" He's talking to my brother

00:29:52.450 --> 00:29:56.720
now who was older and already had graduated
and at the time was working for my dad as

00:29:56.720 --> 00:29:58.269
a construction expediter.

00:29:58.269 --> 00:30:03.789
Anyway, he said "You know, you can use this
and you can make industrial videos."

00:30:03.789 --> 00:30:07.710
'Cause he knew David wanted to get into something
with, you know film.

00:30:07.710 --> 00:30:11.610
And industrial videos were not exactly what
David had in mind.

00:30:11.610 --> 00:30:22.049
[chuckles] But then when David saw this "Groove
Tube" thing, he drove all the way from Chicago.

00:30:22.049 --> 00:30:23.789
He saw it in Chicago.

00:30:23.789 --> 00:30:25.750
Drove up to Madison.

00:30:25.750 --> 00:30:27.179
And started talking a mile a minute.

00:30:27.179 --> 00:30:28.220
"Jerry, we gotta do this.

00:30:28.220 --> 00:30:29.220
Da da dad a da.

00:30:29.220 --> 00:30:30.470
This we can do."

00:30:30.470 --> 00:30:38.429
So we got a hold of the video tape equipment
and actually David just ran into Jim Abrams

00:30:38.429 --> 00:30:39.710
in Milwaukee.

00:30:39.710 --> 00:30:44.529
And Jim at the time was working as a private
investigator for a law firm.

00:30:44.529 --> 00:30:45.559
[laughter]

00:30:45.559 --> 00:30:53.629
And he, and the three of us found ourselves
in the basement of our house with this video

00:30:53.629 --> 00:30:55.700
tape equipment.

00:30:55.700 --> 00:30:56.929
And just having a blast.

00:30:56.929 --> 00:31:01.210
And it was the greatest thing because, you
know, you could even though it was that machine

00:31:01.210 --> 00:31:04.080
I described earlier, in black and white then.

00:31:04.080 --> 00:31:05.470
But you could play it back right away.

00:31:05.470 --> 00:31:07.420
You didn't have to send it out to be developed.

00:31:07.420 --> 00:31:12.639
And there was no cost to it, you know, unless
you bought another reel of tape.

00:31:12.639 --> 00:31:14.110
But even that wasn't very much.

00:31:14.110 --> 00:31:15.110
And you could erase it.

00:31:15.110 --> 00:31:19.080
And it was just like, we had a, we just had
a blast.

00:31:19.080 --> 00:31:23.100
And we laughed and it was the most fun thing.

00:31:23.100 --> 00:31:28.470
And then at some point we said, well, "We
gotta show this to people."

00:31:28.470 --> 00:31:32.389
We did show, we collected a reel of these
funny things we'd done.

00:31:32.389 --> 00:31:33.860
We showed the people and they laughed.

00:31:33.860 --> 00:31:36.940
We said "OK, we gotta do something, we gotta
put this."

00:31:36.940 --> 00:31:40.139
It's like Mickey Rooney and Judy Garland "Hey,
let's do a show!"

00:31:40.139 --> 00:31:45.630
So anyway, it's a long story but finally we
got it all together.

00:31:45.630 --> 00:31:46.929
We opened at University of Wisconsin.

00:31:46.929 --> 00:31:52.020
There were a bunch of live skits and then
a bunch of video tape and a little bit of

00:31:52.020 --> 00:31:53.120
film stuff.

00:31:53.120 --> 00:31:56.700
And it was just anything goes, this was 1970.

00:31:56.700 --> 00:32:02.720
And it was just at the time that it was OK
to laugh again.

00:32:02.720 --> 00:32:05.730
Because this is just post-Vietnam.

00:32:05.730 --> 00:32:10.700
Protests and everything at that time was very
political.

00:32:10.700 --> 00:32:11.700
The Committee.

00:32:11.700 --> 00:32:12.700
The Second City.

00:32:12.700 --> 00:32:14.620
These groups would do a lot of political material.

00:32:14.620 --> 00:32:18.919
And we were just, you know, zany.

00:32:18.919 --> 00:32:22.899
We didn't do any political material, really.

00:32:22.899 --> 00:32:27.370
And got skewered for that occasionally in
reviews.

00:32:27.370 --> 00:32:33.960
You know, but basically the show was a success
We weren't making a lot of money on it, but

00:32:33.960 --> 00:32:35.450
enough to buy more equipment.

00:32:35.450 --> 00:32:37.360
But we all had other, I was in school.

00:32:37.360 --> 00:32:44.429
And Jim and David had jobs and stuff, and
so for, we, at some point it became not just

00:32:44.429 --> 00:32:45.429
a lark.

00:32:45.429 --> 00:32:48.570
But like, you know, we're really into this.

00:32:48.570 --> 00:32:49.570
You know?

00:32:49.570 --> 00:32:50.889
And we gotta, we don't wanna stop this.

00:32:50.889 --> 00:32:52.590
But we can't make a living from it here.

00:32:52.590 --> 00:32:55.039
So let's go to Los Angeles.

00:32:55.039 --> 00:32:57.779
So we packed up everything in a big U-Haul
truck.

00:32:57.779 --> 00:33:01.450
The boards from the stage, the costumes, the
wiring.

00:33:01.450 --> 00:33:04.059
And we moved out to Los Angeles.

00:33:04.059 --> 00:33:05.520
And did the show there.

00:33:05.520 --> 00:33:11.149
And so now to skip to the movie.

00:33:11.149 --> 00:33:12.929
Actually when we first came to Los Angeles.

00:33:12.929 --> 00:33:14.120
We didn't know what we wanted to be.

00:33:14.120 --> 00:33:16.529
I mean, a performing group.

00:33:16.529 --> 00:33:17.529
Television.

00:33:17.529 --> 00:33:18.529
Writers.

00:33:18.529 --> 00:33:22.749
I don't think we ever thought of ourselves
really so much as directors.

00:33:22.749 --> 00:33:26.950
We turned to that sort of because we wanted
control of our material.

00:33:26.950 --> 00:33:32.350
But not because we were like born to do that.

00:33:32.350 --> 00:33:35.210
Which is pretty obvious if you look at any
of our movies.

00:33:35.210 --> 00:33:36.260
[laughter]

00:33:36.260 --> 00:33:44.419
But we you know, at some point we said "OK,
film really is our media.

00:33:44.419 --> 00:33:50.799
It's where we can take time and I don't know,
it's just, you know we're not that prolific.

00:33:50.799 --> 00:33:54.289
We really like to take time to get.

00:33:54.289 --> 00:33:57.620
We wanna be able to take the time to get it
right and have something that would last and

00:33:57.620 --> 00:34:00.909
not just, you know.

00:34:00.909 --> 00:34:02.450
Disappear after a week."

00:34:02.450 --> 00:34:03.450
Or whatever.

00:34:03.450 --> 00:34:13.329
So we, David saw John Landis, who directed
"Animal House" and "The Blues brothers", those

00:34:13.329 --> 00:34:14.329
films.

00:34:14.329 --> 00:34:17.169
But this was just after his first movie "Schlock"
and he was on the Tonight Show because he

00:34:17.169 --> 00:34:21.720
was a 21 year old kid who had directed a film.

00:34:21.720 --> 00:34:25.179
And David thought, geez, 21, maybe he'll talk
to us.

00:34:25.179 --> 00:34:28.200
I mean, because we didn't know anybody still.

00:34:28.200 --> 00:34:33.900
And we had done this all but we didn't, we
had, we didn't know anybody in the movie business.

00:34:33.900 --> 00:34:40.070
And so David called him and he was nice enough,
he invited him to the show.

00:34:40.070 --> 00:34:42.550
He came to the show and we took him out to
lunch.

00:34:42.550 --> 00:34:46.190
And I remember he gave us a, we said "How
do you write a movie script?"

00:34:46.190 --> 00:34:52.819
And he gave us the script to "American Werewolf
in London" [laughter] which happened much

00:34:52.819 --> 00:34:54.089
later, you know.

00:34:54.089 --> 00:35:01.830
But we, so we used the form and that's when
we stared to write the first draft of "Airplane"

00:35:01.830 --> 00:35:09.701
and then when we couldn't get that going,
we decided that maybe a way to get a movie

00:35:09.701 --> 00:35:16.890
going was to do a really low budget film of
different bits.

00:35:16.890 --> 00:35:20.380
And there had already, "Groove Tube" had done
that and been successful.

00:35:20.380 --> 00:35:24.300
So again we followed in the steps of "Groove
Tube."

00:35:24.300 --> 00:35:27.510
Does that answer your question?

00:35:27.510 --> 00:35:28.510
More than you ever wanted.

00:35:28.510 --> 00:35:29.510
Yeah, go ahead.

00:35:29.510 --> 00:35:30.510
[laughter]

00:35:30.510 --> 00:35:35.050
&gt;&gt;male #4: I was gonna ask you since you directed
with the trio and by yourself.

00:35:35.050 --> 00:35:36.309
Kind of, the differences.

00:35:36.309 --> 00:35:42.570
And what it's like to have three, directing
with two other people with you.

00:35:42.570 --> 00:35:47.030
&gt;&gt;Jerry: When you direct by yourself you get
all of the credit and all of the blame.

00:35:47.030 --> 00:35:48.030
[laughs]

00:35:48.030 --> 00:35:52.059
But, and it actually is really good to share
both.

00:35:52.059 --> 00:35:53.230
Ironically.

00:35:53.230 --> 00:35:55.450
It's great.

00:35:55.450 --> 00:35:57.400
In the days of success.

00:35:57.400 --> 00:36:00.339
It was great to go "Alright!

00:36:00.339 --> 00:36:03.890
Guys!" because you can't just go out in public
and say "Hey!

00:36:03.890 --> 00:36:06.110
I made that movie!" you know.

00:36:06.110 --> 00:36:09.310
So it's just sort of, we had a, Dave and Jim
and I grew up together.

00:36:09.310 --> 00:36:10.950
We were, Dave and I are brothers.

00:36:10.950 --> 00:36:14.380
It was, you know, we had a, it was a great
trio.

00:36:14.380 --> 00:36:18.180
Not that we didn't argue and you know, beat
each other up a little bit.

00:36:18.180 --> 00:36:20.700
But we really, we loved each other.

00:36:20.700 --> 00:36:24.580
And we needed each other and it was great.

00:36:24.580 --> 00:36:29.339
I think what happened is eventually, particularly
when we stopped doing satire.

00:36:29.339 --> 00:36:33.420
I mean "Ruthless People" was a little harder
'cause it was a comedy but it wasn't a satire.

00:36:33.420 --> 00:36:39.250
So there were more arguments 'cause that movie
could've gone in different directions.

00:36:39.250 --> 00:36:41.520
Different filmmakers could've made different
films.

00:36:41.520 --> 00:36:50.670
Whereas "Airplane" or "Naked Gun", there was
really only one film to be made of that.

00:36:50.670 --> 00:36:59.300
Anyway, so it, we, and also I think that when
we started we really didn't have the courage.

00:36:59.300 --> 00:37:04.119
I don't think we would have, I don't think
if either of us, any of us, had come out here

00:37:04.119 --> 00:37:09.220
alone we would have ever had the nerve to
direct a film on our own.

00:37:09.220 --> 00:37:10.450
So it just took a while for us.

00:37:10.450 --> 00:37:13.930
Because like I said, we didn't come out like,
with, you know.

00:37:13.930 --> 00:37:19.010
We, directing really takes sort of a lot of
kind of nerve.

00:37:19.010 --> 00:37:22.099
Or it takes some bravado.

00:37:22.099 --> 00:37:24.080
It takes some confidence.

00:37:24.080 --> 00:37:26.670
It, which we didn't have.

00:37:26.670 --> 00:37:29.240
You know, individually, I don't think.

00:37:29.240 --> 00:37:33.809
And so but we did collectively.

00:37:33.809 --> 00:37:36.700
And so, but yeah.

00:37:36.700 --> 00:37:41.589
Directing alone, at some point, you kind of,
it is nice to make all the decisions.

00:37:41.589 --> 00:37:44.690
It is nice to make the film you wanna make.

00:37:44.690 --> 00:37:46.941
And it's, you know it's a mixed thing.

00:37:46.941 --> 00:37:48.700
I mean, I do, I enjoy that.

00:37:48.700 --> 00:37:55.840
And I've liked that experience but on the
other hand, I don't know, the three of us

00:37:55.840 --> 00:37:57.130
was great.

00:37:57.130 --> 00:37:58.160
You know?

00:37:58.160 --> 00:37:59.160
So.

00:37:59.160 --> 00:38:02.589
It's they're both, it's both good.

00:38:02.589 --> 00:38:03.660
You have the mic, so go ahead.

00:38:03.660 --> 00:38:07.490
&gt;&gt;male #5: One of the things I was struck
by watching you tonight was how well a lot,

00:38:07.490 --> 00:38:09.030
so many of the jokes have held up.

00:38:09.030 --> 00:38:11.990
And you were saying you didn't expect that
it would be around for decades.

00:38:11.990 --> 00:38:12.990
&gt;&gt;Jerry: Yeah.

00:38:12.990 --> 00:38:16.109
&gt;&gt;male #5: But did you consciously do this
mix of jokes?

00:38:16.109 --> 00:38:20.540
To really try to balance it between these
very period, very specific that you have to

00:38:20.540 --> 00:38:23.240
