00:45:01.060 --> 00:45:08.569
But he, and there was, and then there's food
poisoning and the whole deal.

00:45:08.569 --> 00:45:13.130
But there actually is that line in that, in
"Zero Hour".

00:45:13.130 --> 00:45:19.119
We took verbatim where he says "The life of
everybody on board this plane depends on just

00:45:19.119 --> 00:45:20.119
two things.

00:45:20.119 --> 00:45:24.069
Finding someone back there who not only can
fly this plane, but who didn't have fish for

00:45:24.069 --> 00:45:25.069
dinner."

00:45:25.069 --> 00:45:26.069
[laughter]

00:45:26.069 --> 00:45:29.869
You know, stole that verbatim.

00:45:29.869 --> 00:45:32.540
[laughter] Not a line changed.

00:45:32.540 --> 00:45:38.020
And we, and it's just must be funny if I don't
know if Hall Bartlett who wrote that ever

00:45:38.020 --> 00:45:40.580
saw "Airplane".

00:45:40.580 --> 00:45:43.900
But it gets a big laugh in "Airplane" and
you know.

00:45:43.900 --> 00:45:44.900
[laughter]

00:45:44.900 --> 00:45:47.569
&gt;&gt;male #7: I was curious, too, about it being
your first time directing and the three of

00:45:47.569 --> 00:45:49.770
you, all three of you, your first time.

00:45:49.770 --> 00:45:52.359
How much, if any, that you rehearsed?

00:45:52.359 --> 00:45:57.730
How did you approach the actors like Robert
Stack and Lloyd Bridges and said "Hey, we

00:45:57.730 --> 00:45:59.460
loved you in this" you know, that kind a thing?

00:45:59.460 --> 00:46:04.030
And how was it, if what you remember of your
impressions directing it when you were actually

00:46:04.030 --> 00:46:05.030
shooting.

00:46:05.030 --> 00:46:07.190
Were you guys crazy nervous or were you confident
by then?

00:46:07.190 --> 00:46:08.520
Or was it a fun set?

00:46:08.520 --> 00:46:10.130
Or was it really serious, or?

00:46:10.130 --> 00:46:13.380
&gt;&gt;Jerry: I don't remember sleeping a lot the
night before the first day.

00:46:13.380 --> 00:46:19.750
But it was, but we were, it was, I look at,
look back at it as one of the most fun experiences

00:46:19.750 --> 00:46:22.020
in my career.

00:46:22.020 --> 00:46:25.110
It was a, just exciting and a blast.

00:46:25.110 --> 00:46:28.742
And not that any movie, you're always like,
"Oh my God, what are we gonna do.

00:46:28.742 --> 00:46:36.390
This isn't working" [inaudible] but you know,
but, the actors in terms of how we got them.

00:46:36.390 --> 00:46:47.280
We, some, Howard Koch was helpful because
he sort of, you know, was respected.

00:46:47.280 --> 00:46:49.270
And told these guys that we were OK.

00:46:49.270 --> 00:46:51.480
A lot of them like Peter Graves really didn't.

00:46:51.480 --> 00:46:58.940
He actually thought the script was atrocious
[laughter] And he, you know, but how I got

00:46:58.940 --> 00:47:03.180
all these guys to meet, it was actually Peter
Graves' wife loved it.

00:47:03.180 --> 00:47:05.790
And his kids thought it was great.

00:47:05.790 --> 00:47:07.100
And they were sort of encouraging them.

00:47:07.100 --> 00:47:09.010
And he said "Why do you want me?

00:47:09.010 --> 00:47:10.319
Don't you want one of the big?

00:47:10.319 --> 00:47:11.319
Like Dom Delouise?

00:47:11.319 --> 00:47:15.480
Or one of the big comó" Well, you know, at
the time, he was a bit.

00:47:15.480 --> 00:47:19.320
I don't know if that's the right name, but
whoever was in the Jack Lemmon.

00:47:19.320 --> 00:47:20.320
I don't know.

00:47:20.320 --> 00:47:21.460
Walter Matthau.

00:47:21.460 --> 00:47:22.460
Whatever.

00:47:22.460 --> 00:47:27.670
But we said, we said "No, we think you'll
be funnier."

00:47:27.670 --> 00:47:31.810
[laughs] And we explained that we just wanted
to play it straight.

00:47:31.810 --> 00:47:37.050
We wanted him to be just like he was in Mission
Impossible or Fury or any of these shows that

00:47:37.050 --> 00:47:39.049
he'd ever done.

00:47:39.049 --> 00:47:41.069
And they were all kinda different.

00:47:41.069 --> 00:47:42.890
Peter Graves is a lovely guy.

00:47:42.890 --> 00:47:44.299
Wonderful, wonderful guy.

00:47:44.299 --> 00:47:48.380
And he just, he didn't really completely get
it.

00:47:48.380 --> 00:47:49.380
But he loved it later.

00:47:49.380 --> 00:47:50.700
When he saw it.

00:47:50.700 --> 00:47:51.700
[laughter]

00:47:51.700 --> 00:47:57.480
And his wife was just hysterical in the first
screening for after the movie was finished

00:47:57.480 --> 00:47:58.480
for everybody.

00:47:58.480 --> 00:48:06.329
And, but he just, he kind of was just totally
cooperative.

00:48:06.329 --> 00:48:07.329
You know.

00:48:07.329 --> 00:48:08.660
So we would tell him a lot.

00:48:08.660 --> 00:48:11.470
"OK say the line.

00:48:11.470 --> 00:48:13.140
Then say this line.

00:48:13.140 --> 00:48:14.140
Look up.

00:48:14.140 --> 00:48:16.130
Say that line, then look down, then look back."

00:48:16.130 --> 00:48:18.390
Like particularly with the little boy.

00:48:18.390 --> 00:48:21.809
That's kinda tricky stuff.

00:48:21.809 --> 00:48:24.010
[laughter]

00:48:24.010 --> 00:48:30.400
So, we really explained to him when he could
look at him, 'cause if he looks at him and

00:48:30.400 --> 00:48:32.880
says "Have you ever seen a grown man naked?"
it's not gonna work.

00:48:32.880 --> 00:48:38.261
[laughter] You know so he has to say "Joey,
have you ever seen a grown man na--?"

00:48:38.261 --> 00:48:44.481
So, you know we, but he was totally cooperative
and played it just like, you know, and it

00:48:44.481 --> 00:48:46.660
was great.

00:48:46.660 --> 00:48:50.040
Lloyd Bridges was a little different.

00:48:50.040 --> 00:48:55.980
He was the one and Lloyd, I think, is fantastic
in the film.

00:48:55.980 --> 00:49:00.630
But you can kinda see that he was the one
that wanted to be funny a little bit.

00:49:00.630 --> 00:49:01.630
You know?

00:49:01.630 --> 00:49:09.550
He was the one who is, who I think, I felt
was the, had the most trouble controlling.

00:49:09.550 --> 00:49:12.030
But in the end, it kind of worked.

00:49:12.030 --> 00:49:15.420
And it was fine and it gave us different levels.

00:49:15.420 --> 00:49:22.319
And so I like, in a lot of situations, it
just, it we had some argument but it worked

00:49:22.319 --> 00:49:23.319
out great.

00:49:23.319 --> 00:49:25.049
And he was also a great guy.

00:49:25.049 --> 00:49:27.089
He was a great guy, Lloyd.

00:49:27.089 --> 00:49:29.720
So that was already great.

00:49:29.720 --> 00:49:30.720
That was good.

00:49:30.720 --> 00:49:37.380
Robert Stack was a good, Robert Stack is not
really a comedian, but he got it.

00:49:37.380 --> 00:49:44.020
He got it and he looked and there was one
moment actually in rehearsals where Lloyd

00:49:44.020 --> 00:49:50.010
Bridges was asking "Why would my character
say this line?"

00:49:50.010 --> 00:49:52.520
You know, it's like, trying to think about
it really.

00:49:52.520 --> 00:49:53.520
Think it through.

00:49:53.520 --> 00:49:54.520
[laughter]

00:49:54.520 --> 00:49:55.520
Like an actor's role.

00:49:55.520 --> 00:50:00.390
You know, this is not, Stanislavsky will not
help you here.

00:50:00.390 --> 00:50:02.180
[laughter]

00:50:02.180 --> 00:50:07.110
So he, so but Stack just, you know and we're
kind a still young.

00:50:07.110 --> 00:50:08.110
Rehearsal is--.

00:50:08.110 --> 00:50:09.110
Young kids.

00:50:09.110 --> 00:50:12.010
So for us, you have to understand these guys
were major stars and heroes for us.

00:50:12.010 --> 00:50:14.490
Because we grew up with all of them.

00:50:14.490 --> 00:50:20.349
But Stack just said, he said "Lloyd, who cares,
there's a spear going in the wall behind you

00:50:20.349 --> 00:50:22.640
and a watermelon falling in front of me.

00:50:22.640 --> 00:50:23.930
Just keep talking Lloyd.

00:50:23.930 --> 00:50:26.650
Nobody's lookin' at us."

00:50:26.650 --> 00:50:28.380
You know?

00:50:28.380 --> 00:50:29.380
[laughter]

00:50:29.380 --> 00:50:34.650
Which was great 'cause he really, Stack was
just, he kind of, he knew.

00:50:34.650 --> 00:50:37.089
He said "We're the Stooges."

00:50:37.089 --> 00:50:38.640
But he was willing to do that.

00:50:38.640 --> 00:50:41.521
And thought it was appropriate and all.

00:50:41.521 --> 00:50:43.270
And it, lovely, lovely guy.

00:50:43.270 --> 00:50:44.790
Robert Stack.

00:50:44.790 --> 00:50:47.340
And then, Leslie Neilsen.

00:50:47.340 --> 00:50:52.430
Who then, I remember the casting agent was
couldn't understand why we wanted Leslie Neilsen.

00:50:52.430 --> 00:50:58.760
He kept saying "Leslie Neilsen is the guy
you go to the night before, when you can't

00:50:58.760 --> 00:50:59.760
get anyone else."

00:50:59.760 --> 00:51:02.119
And we said "No, no, he's got that thing.

00:51:02.119 --> 00:51:05.220
Really, he'll be perfect for the doctor."

00:51:05.220 --> 00:51:11.180
And Leslie Neilsen was the one that was a
fish in water.

00:51:11.180 --> 00:51:13.890
Leslie said later "I would have paid you guys
to do this."

00:51:13.890 --> 00:51:14.890
Would he?

00:51:14.890 --> 00:51:15.890
[laughter]

00:51:15.890 --> 00:51:16.950
Yeah, no, but I think he meant it.

00:51:16.950 --> 00:51:22.270
And Leslie, it's interesting, people always
ask "were you surprised that he was so good

00:51:22.270 --> 00:51:23.619
at comedy?"

00:51:23.619 --> 00:51:30.930
And my reaction is really, "No, I was more
surprised that he did drama all those years."

00:51:30.930 --> 00:51:32.640
Because he really is an nutty guy.

00:51:32.640 --> 00:51:37.030
It's not like he's a serious guy but he turns
on a thing and he can do comedy.

00:51:37.030 --> 00:51:41.670
It was, he's a nutty guy who can get into
that serious mode and be the captain of the

00:51:41.670 --> 00:51:43.109
titanic.

00:51:43.109 --> 00:51:47.980
Or the, what's that movie, the, anyway.

00:51:47.980 --> 00:51:49.089
[laughter]

00:51:49.089 --> 00:51:51.420
The movie where he says "Oh my God."

00:51:51.420 --> 00:51:53.420
When the tidal wave comes.

00:51:53.420 --> 00:51:54.420
Anyway.

00:51:54.420 --> 00:51:59.099
So, the, before we're done someone has to
think of the name of that.

00:51:59.099 --> 00:52:00.390
"Poseidon Adventure."

00:52:00.390 --> 00:52:01.690
Thank you.

00:52:01.690 --> 00:52:04.510
So, but he was, Leslie was a joy.

00:52:04.510 --> 00:52:06.690
And he was an anarchist like we were.

00:52:06.690 --> 00:52:08.311
&gt;&gt;male audience member: What about Kareem
Abdul Jabar?

00:52:08.311 --> 00:52:09.311
Do you remember?

00:52:09.311 --> 00:52:10.311
&gt;&gt;Jerry: Well, Kareem was great too.

00:52:10.311 --> 00:52:13.470
We actually wrote the role for Pete Rose but
it was during baseball season so we couldn't

00:52:13.470 --> 00:52:15.289
get Pete Rose.

00:52:15.289 --> 00:52:22.300
[laughter] So we decided to cast, we decided
Kareem would be good, we'd go after Kareem.

00:52:22.300 --> 00:52:27.059
So we went Kareem and I think we offered him
$25,000.

00:52:27.059 --> 00:52:31.880
And his agent called back and says "It's gotta
be, he wants 30.

00:52:31.880 --> 00:52:35.000
Because he wants to buy an oriental rug and
it costs 30."

00:52:35.000 --> 00:52:41.700
And that's the only reason he'll do it.

00:52:41.700 --> 00:52:43.230
[laughter]

00:52:43.230 --> 00:52:48.039
And I thought to myself, this is the greatest
line I've ever heard from an agent.

00:52:48.039 --> 00:52:49.180
[laughter]

00:52:49.180 --> 00:52:51.640
I want this guy to represent me.

00:52:51.640 --> 00:52:52.750
[laughter]

00:52:52.750 --> 00:52:55.610
And so, but we really, really wanted him.

00:52:55.610 --> 00:53:02.530
And of course even $5,000 on a three million
dollar movie was really, is a lot.

00:53:02.530 --> 00:53:04.880
So we said "Yes."

00:53:04.880 --> 00:53:06.660
So excited to have Kareem.

00:53:06.660 --> 00:53:14.520
And like two weeks later, there's an article
in a little blurb in TIME Magazine featuring,

00:53:14.520 --> 00:53:20.290
that shows Kareem in front of a big oriental
rug that he'd just bought.

00:53:20.290 --> 00:53:21.290
[laugher]

00:53:21.290 --> 00:53:22.710
For $30,000.

00:53:22.710 --> 00:53:24.829
At some auction.

00:53:24.829 --> 00:53:25.829
So who knew?

00:53:25.829 --> 00:53:26.829
But Kareem was great.

00:53:26.829 --> 00:53:36.099
Kareem was, it's funny, I was, Kareem was
not, you know, the, a skilled actor.

00:53:36.099 --> 00:53:38.160
But he was also lovely.

00:53:38.160 --> 00:53:39.240
Really a good guy.

00:53:39.240 --> 00:53:43.089
Kind, of, you know, took a bit to get to know,
you know.

00:53:43.089 --> 00:53:46.420
He's not like gregarious a bit.

00:53:46.420 --> 00:53:49.369
He's a little more shy around people.

00:53:49.369 --> 00:53:52.630
And of course, your neck, I mean, he's so
tall.

00:53:52.630 --> 00:53:58.800
But he's really, but I grew very fond of Kareem
and I actually just saw him a year ago.

00:53:58.800 --> 00:54:01.539
And it was funny.

00:54:01.539 --> 00:54:09.730
He's, he says he that he always every time
he goes on an airplane, people, like the pilots

00:54:09.730 --> 00:54:12.000
invite him up to the cockpit or whatever.

00:54:12.000 --> 00:54:13.000
[laughter]

00:54:13.000 --> 00:54:20.130
Stuff like that, and I thought, that's movie
must be really powerful if they're inviting

00:54:20.130 --> 00:54:23.210
a guy named Kareem up to the cockpit.

00:54:23.210 --> 00:54:24.820
[laughter]

00:54:24.820 --> 00:54:25.820
In this day and age.

00:54:25.820 --> 00:54:27.339
But no, no, no.

00:54:27.339 --> 00:54:28.940
He was great.

00:54:28.940 --> 00:54:34.910
And you know, really lucky to have had him
in the movie.

00:54:34.910 --> 00:54:37.530
It's hard to imagine it without him.

00:54:37.530 --> 00:54:38.530
Yeah.

